Research Question

Shira Wild, Maayan Aviram and Noa Radin

Does the size of a certain age group out of the population in a state affect the number of people that got infected or died from Corona virus in that state?

We expect to see a connection between the proportion of specific age group, to the amount of covid cases/deaths. For Example, in a state with a lot of elders, we expect to see bigger proportion of covid cases/deaths - like in Italy, where the large elderly population has been poses a challenge in slowing the number of coronavirus deaths.

First we will load the covid_cases data set:

Covid_cases <- read_rds(here::here("data", "covid_cases.rds"))

Now load the age_groups_by_state dataset which includes information about the population of each age group in the different states in USA:

Age_groups_dataset <- read.csv("age_groups_by_state.csv")

# Make a column named "Location" with the shortcuts of the state - for the join 
colnames(Age_groups_dataset)[1] <- "Location"
vec <- c("AL","AK", "AZ", "AR", "CA", "CO", "CT", "DE", "DC", "FL", "GA", "HI", "ID", "IL", "IN", "IA", "KS", "KY", "LA", "ME", "MD", "MA", "MI", "MN", "MS", "MO", "MT", "NE", "NV" ,"NH", "NJ", "NM", "NY", "NC", "ND", "OH", "OK", "OR", "PA", "RI", "SC", "SD", "TN", "TX", "UT", "VT", "VA", "WA", "WV", "WI", "WY", "PR")
Age_groups_dataset$State <- vec

colnames(Age_groups_dataset)[2:7] <- c("0-18", "19-25", "26-34", "35-54", "55-64", "65 and over")

# Preparing the joined dataset with "Age_groups_dataset" - Function:

prepare <- function(dataset){
  # join the dataset with the Age_groups_dataset
  ages_and_combined <- dataset %>% 
  right_join(Age_groups_dataset, by = "State")
  
  # calculate the percentage of total_deaths and total_cases
  ages_and_combined$total_deaths<- ages_and_combined$total_deaths/ages_and_combined$total_cases
  ages_and_combined$total_cases<- ages_and_combined$total_cases/ages_and_combined$Total
  
  # create pivot table
  ages_groups <- c("0-18", "19-25", "26-34", "35-54", "55-64", "65 and over")
  
  pivoted_ages <- ages_and_combined %>% 
    pivot_longer(cols = all_of(ages_groups), names_to = "age_group", values_to = "Percentage")
  
  # calculate the percentage of each age group
  pivoted_ages$Percentage<- pivoted_ages$Percentage/pivoted_ages$Total
  return(pivoted_ages)
}

After that, in the prepare function, we will join it with the covid_cases dataset, and use pivot_longer for the age groups’ columns, and start to look for connection between the datasets.

The connection between the proportion of specific age group, to the amount of covid cases/deaths.

# Summarise the amount of cases and dead for each state into "Sum_cases_dead"
Sum_cases_dead <- Covid_cases%>%
  group_by(State, Region) %>%
  summarise(total_deaths = sum(Daily_new_death), total_cases = sum(Daily_new_cases),.groups="drop")

All_dates <- prepare(Sum_cases_dead)
glimpse(All_dates)

This is the combined and pivoted dataset, the column Percentage is the proportion of the age group out of the country.

We can notice that logically the proportion of the total_deaths or total_cases is constant for all of the age groups in a country, so that the ‘y’ axis will be constant for each age_group in the facets of each graph. The Percentage is changing according to the age_group. That also means that the high dots that we will see in each graph are the countries with the highest amount of cases and deaths.

First, we will check the connection on COVID cases:

ggplot(data = All_dates, aes(x = Percentage, y = total_cases, color = as.factor(age_group))) +
  geom_point(stat="identity")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45,hjust=1)) +
  facet_wrap(~age_group)+
  scale_color_manual(values=c("gold", "gold3", "lightgoldenrod2", "goldenrod2", "darkgoldenrod1", "darkgoldenrod4"))+
  labs(title = "The connection between the proportion of age group in a state ", subtitle = "to the proportion of covid cases in a state, by age group", x= "Proportion of age group", y = "Proportion of covid cases", color = "Age Group")

We can NOT see a clear connection between the amount of different age groups from the population in a state to the level of COVID cases/deaths. The reason is probably that with the time, we learned that COVID is attacking everyone, without connection to the age.

Maybe at the beginning of the pandemic there were more elders that was infected/died, and towards the end, the elders were much more careful and a balance was created.

So let’s check if at the beginning of the pandemic, there was a connection between the proportion of the age group in a state to the proportion of cases/deaths.

We can see slight connection at the groups of 0-18 and 65 and over. Let’s see if there is an incline in the average amount of deaths in countries that has less than 15% of elders, to countries that has more than 15% of elders:

# Maximum proportion of dead
Max_death <- (Beginning%>%
  filter(total_deaths==max(total_deaths)))$total_deaths[1]

# Average of the deaths percentage (less than 15% elders)
Average_deaths_less <- Beginning %>%
  filter(Percentage<=0.15 & age_group=="65 and over") %>%
  summarise(Average_deaths = mean(total_deaths))
Percentage_less <- Average_deaths_less$Average_deaths/Max_death*100

# Average of the deaths percentage (more than 15% elders)
Average_deaths_more<- Beginning %>%
  filter(Percentage>=0.15 & age_group=="65 and over") %>%
  summarise(Average_deaths = mean(total_deaths))
Percentage_more <- Average_deaths_more$Average_deaths/Max_death*100

cat(paste0("The Percentage of deaths among states that there is less than 15% of elders in is: ",round(Percentage_less, 2),"%", "\n", "The Percentage of deaths among states that there is more than 15% of elders in is: ",round(Percentage_more, 2),"%", "\n", "There is an incline of ", round(Percentage_more-Percentage_less, 2),  "% in the amount of deaths in countries with more elders."))
## The Percentage of deaths among states that there is less than 15% of elders in is: 39.76%
## The Percentage of deaths among states that there is more than 15% of elders in is: 46.93%
## There is an incline of 7.16% in the amount of deaths in countries with more elders.

Overall, we can see that there is a slight connection for two groups. At the 65 and over age group, there are more deaths in the countries that has higher proportion of elders. In addition, we can see that for the group of 0-18- children, there are less deaths at the countries that has higher proportion of children.

For conclusion

We cannot say that the answer to our question is yes, but we did find that for certain periods of time - until April 30th, 2020, and in the peak of the pandemic, at January, 2021, the size of a certain age group - elders or children in a state, affect the number of people that died from Corona virus in that state.
